subject: Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria
messages: [{'account_id': 28062, 'date': '2020-09-30 12:33:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 28062, 'date': '2020-09-30 13:09:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-28 15:47:45.000000000', 'message': 'Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ibb2263aa7bcc1166b527e5d99ef2ce8940d4259c

commit_message:
Invoke swift_rsync_fix container for every deployment

swift_rsync_fix container was introduced to disable usage of pid file
by rsync process to avoid issue caused by stale pid file left inside
container.
However this container isn't invoked when overcloud stack is updated
and that pid file is revived and left after overclouds get updated,
because puppet regenerates rsync.conf with pid file enabled.
This patch makes sure that swift_rsync_fix container is invoked
everytime when overcloud is updated so that pid file is always
disabled during deployments.

Closes-Bug: #1884671
Change-Id: Ie7c5573dc93c969d1bdc668d73c97da3608e1bc2

commit_message:
Add source_ip_prefix and destination_ip_prefix to metering label rules

As proposed in the RFE and then approved in the spec, we are adding to
the neutron metering rules two new parameters. The source IP prefix, and
destination IP prefix.

Partially-Implements: https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1889431
RFE: https://bugs.launchpad.net/neutron/+bug/1889431

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/746142/

commit_message:
Update status message if new version of vault is installed

As part of snap auto-updates, new versions of vault get installed when
available. But manual intervention is required to restart the vault
service. This patch updates the status message to inform the same to
the user.

Closes-Bug: #1895577

Change-Id: I995069bc151c1db5061c52b9d89d014be6b6a556

commit_message:
Skip update of vip sg if lb is gone

It's possible that while ensuring the listener,
the load balancer was not present anymore and
consequently there is not need to update the vip
port sg. This commit enforces that the update only
happens if a listener was created and the vip is
present.

Change-Id: I3f104062887626f7b374993b5466fc962ccca85a

commit_message:
Simplify legacy hieradata check to avoid false positive.

It seems that the current check for legacy hieradata can be fooled by
the way os-apply-config get its cached data.  This simplify the check
to avoid those false positives.

This a stable/ocata patch only as it's the transition between old and
new hiera mechanism.  For master, the stricter check is kept.

Resolves: rhbz#1883838
Change-Id: I53eddcb4e80f1256feb4285fdc7d25a2d70fb593
Closes-Bug: #1680006
(cherry picked from commit 769d0de4d9acb07563202a2ef3d3a0aa1b9542d1)

The Msvm_VirtualSystemSettingData object associated with a VM has a
field named "ChassisAssetTag". The value set in this field is reflected
in Linux VMs in /sys/class/dmi/id/chassis-asset-tag. This value is

commit_message:
vmutils: Adds the ability to modify the VM's chassis asset tag

The Msvm_VirtualSystemSettingData object associated with a VM has a
field named "ChassisAssetTag". The value set in this field is reflected
in Linux VMs in /sys/class/dmi/id/chassis-asset-tag. This value is
checked by cloud-init in order to figure out if it is currently running
inside an OpenStack VM.

The verification above has been introduced in cloud-init [1] in order to
avoid costly metadata probes that aren't needed in non-OpenStack VMs.

Setting the ChassisAssetTag will allow us to pass these checks.

Partially-Fixes: #1895976

[1] https://github.com/canonical/cloud-init/commit/1efa8a0a030794cec68197100f31a856d0d264ab

Change-Id: I50dd761b3df9f2d243ca295f02d20422f6af965e
(cherry picked from commit 78414e71606b37ff2147ee886ee1fd962ef3a911)

commit_message:
[goal] Migrate testing to ubuntu focal
As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Bump the pyflakes to 2.1.1 as min version to run pep8 jobs
on py3.8 which is default python vesion in ubuntu focal.

Bump netaddr to 0.7.20 in lower-constraints.txt
since it is the min version with py3.8 support [2]

Bump psycopg2 to 2.8.4 in lower-constraints.txt
since it is the min version with py3.8 support [3]

Story: #2007865
Task: #40197

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html
[2] https://github.com/netaddr/netaddr/commit/cc2a9bb31fae00f18fcdbd97a29b643581fc2a45
[3] https://pypi.org/project/psycopg2/2.8.4/

Change-Id: I736f141b53d5fb985e5deaa5d77c552ebad6fccd
(cherry picked from commit 44fe8f1c39d9f9ce8eb66c204ce813873c3cc4ae)

commit_message:
Fix handling OctetString for pysnmp

This commit fixes getting MAC address while inspection for iRMC driver.
To remove ord() in retrieving MAC address, it can avoid the following
exception:

  TypeError: ord() expected string of length 1, but int found

Also, this commit sets the following type of mock for UT. So, I add
'pysnmp'[1] into test-requirements.txt and lower-constraints.txt.

  * pysnmp.proto.rfc1902.OctetString
  * pysnmp.proto.rfc1902.Integer32

[1] https://bit.ly/3bDeTCH
Change-Id: I1e013a93854e01a7060e1fc48aac091e7e9b74cb

commit_message:
Adding document on Extended Maintainance testing policy

As communicated in ML thread
- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-June/015499.html

grenade team will only be responsible for maintaining the 'Maintained' stable
branches only not the EM. We will start making the grenade job on EM and oldest
'Maintained' as n-v if they start failing.

This commits document that agreement so that it can be followed consistently.

Change-Id: I615a6b88d39ab1c91fdf57b3393cbbca66833671

commit_message:
vmutils: Adds the ability to modify the VM's chassis asset tag

The Msvm_VirtualSystemSettingData object associated with a VM has a
field named "ChassisAssetTag". The value set in this field is reflected
in Linux VMs in /sys/class/dmi/id/chassis-asset-tag. This value is
checked by cloud-init in order to figure out if it is currently running
inside an OpenStack VM.

The verification above has been introduced in cloud-init [1] in order to
avoid costly metadata probes that aren't needed in non-OpenStack VMs.

Setting the ChassisAssetTag will allow us to pass these checks.

Partially-Fixes: #1895976

[1] https://github.com/canonical/cloud-init/commit/1efa8a0a030794cec68197100f31a856d0d264ab

Change-Id: I50dd761b3df9f2d243ca295f02d20422f6af965e

commit_message:
[goal] Migrate testing to ubuntu focal
As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Bump the pyflakes to 2.1.1 as min version to run pep8 jobs
on py3.8 which is default python vesion in ubuntu focal.

Bump netaddr to 0.7.20 in lower-constraints.txt
since it is the min version with py3.8 support [2]

Bump psycopg2 to 2.8.4 in lower-constraints.txt
since it is the min version with py3.8 support [3]

Story: #2007865
Task: #40197

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html
[2] https://github.com/netaddr/netaddr/commit/cc2a9bb31fae00f18fcdbd97a29b643581fc2a45
[3] https://pypi.org/project/psycopg2/2.8.4/

Change-Id: I736f141b53d5fb985e5deaa5d77c552ebad6fccd

commit_message:
Run tempest install when tempest_run is False

We should run tempest installation when tempest_run is false. We shouldn't
run it only when tempest_install is False.

commit_message:
Use unittest.mock instead of mock

The mock third party library was needed for mock support in py2
runtimes. Since we now only support py36 and later, we can use the
standard lib unittest.mock module instead

Change-Id: Ie0d086d00231911db8bdb4193381f2d18fee3b10

Change-Id: Ibe1fdc9e454bd9bec929b6736c191f09e078f95e
'}, {'created': '2018-01-22 14:10:30.000000000', 'message': 'Adds VMQs support

Some NICs have different hardware offload features available,
including VMQs. Hyper-V is able to allocate VMQs to different
VM NICs, improving the overall network performance.

By default, all VM NICs are spawned requiring VMQs, but the
host NICs might not have enough VMQs available. Thus, in order
to enable VMQs only for desired VMs, the following config option
must be set to False:

[hyperv]
enable_vmqs = False

Setting the config option to False will mean that newly spawned
or resized instances will no longer have VMQs enabled by default.

VMQs will to be requested via the following flavor extra_specs:
hw:vmqs=required.

Change-Id: Ibe1fdc9e454bd9bec929b6736c191f09e078f95e
'}]
commit_message:
Adds VMQs support

Some NICs have different hardware offload features available,
including VMQs. Hyper-V is able to allocate VMQs to different
VM NICs, improving the overall network performance.

By default, all VM NICs are spawned requiring VMQs, but the
host NICs might not have enough VMQs available. Thus, in order
to enable VMQs only for desired VMs, the following config option
must be set to False:

[hyperv]
enable_vmqs = False

Setting the config option to False will mean that newly spawned
or resized instances will no longer have VMQs enabled by default.

VMQs will to be requested via the following flavor extra_specs:
hw:vmqs=required.

Change-Id: Ibe1fdc9e454bd9bec929b6736c191f09e078f95e

> Yeah, correct. We'll need a different setup. Let's not block on

As I see it it would require more than a role i.e a separate playbook, if the health monitor should have a live member to check. I made the following only syntax checked playbook https://gist.github.com/jsm222/352ea6fe7ae4446bed39ed788d738827 I'm not sure the different return variables are used correctly, but the idea is to follow https://docs.openstack.org/devstack/latest/guides/devstack-with-lbaas-v2.html 

Another thing in my EXAMPLE I have resp_timeout > delay but timeout must be less than delay. Also this requirement should be in DOCUMENTATION as octavia api does not seem to error out on that. This requires a new PATCH SET (?), I'll wait with that until I or someone else has further comments."}, {'account_id': 27900, 'date': '2020-09-28 14:30:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

 > must be less than delay. Also this requirement should be in
 > DOCUMENTATION as octavia api does not seem to error out on that.
 > This requires a new PATCH SET (?), I'll wait with that until I or
 > someone else has further comments.

I can think of 2 options:

- do not try to verify Octavia itself. In this case I would vote for writing unittest ensuring module invokes SDK with the expected params

- create https://opendev.org/openstack/openstacksdk/src/branch/master/.zuul.yaml#L135 job with octavia and a complex functional test:

  - create lb
  - create listener
  - create pool
  - create health monitor
  - create member (sadly requires really provisioning VM)
  - drop member
  - drop HM
  - drop pool
  - drop listener
  - drop lb"}, {'account_id': 29260, 'date': '2020-09-28 17:37:44.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 10969, 'date': '2020-09-29 13:23:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 27900, 'date': '2020-09-30 06:31:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]

Mount libpod container volume into collectd container

The collectd-libpod-stats plugin requires additional libpod volumes to
be mounted into the collectd contianer in order to find and track running
containers. This mounts the only additional volume necessary

commit_message:
Some fixes for zuul tenant

https://zuul.opendev.org/t/zuul/config-errors shows:
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
opendev/system-config - zuul.d/infra-prod.yaml

Zuul encountered a syntax error while parsing its configuration in the
repo opendev/system-config on branch master.  The error was:

  Unknown projects: opendev/ansible-role-puppet
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

Add the repo to the zuul tenant.

Still, a few errors remain - one step at a time;)

Change-Id: I5d91dc7fac924609683f3321a9d49ecb4a522830

commit_message:
Assume Grafana and Ceph Dashboard to be on the storage or ctlplane nets

Both Grafana and the Ceph Dashboard when deployed by ceph-ansible
will be always listening on the storage frontend network.

Change-Id: I3481ddfeeb5603e0e31e4afd26e4218df5defd11

commit_message:
Ensure klb handler reacretes lb

When user manually deletes the load balancer for one specific service
we need to recreate the load balanacer.

This commit makes sure that the load balancer is recreated when the
service is updated.

Change-Id: I47cf26bf50bba865d727221c8df09bce01a9935a

commit_message:
Fix hacking min version to 3.0.1

flake8 new release 3.8.0 added new checks and gate pep8
job start failing. hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to
avoid bringing in a new version with new checks.

Though it is fixed in latest hacking but 2.0 and 3.0 has cap for
flake8 as <4.0.0 which mean flake8 new version 3.9.0 can also
break the pep8 job if new check are added.

To avoid similar gate break in future, we need to bump the hacking min
version.

Also removing the hacking and other related dep from lower-constraints file
as theose are blacklisted requirements and does not need to be present
there.

- http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014828.html

Change-Id: Id693765fa9216f880d7105bbac3cd60f2db8500c

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for tacker

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for tacker.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: I93ddea17c8df77e8dd4d177dc564aa9f319baaf9
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

commit_message:
Add vine to lower-constraints

The newest vine release (5.0.0) is incompatible with the version of amqp
used on stable branches and results in test errors[1]:

  "AttributeError: False does not have the attribute 'info'"

Ensure the lower-constraints tox environment uses the same version of
vine as defined in upper-constraints.txt.

[1] https://zuul.opendev.org/t/openstack/build/78dfcdd4272241459fb904aa70600e5b

commit_message:
Adjust jobs for devstack WSGI mode default

Devstack is switching the default glance operational model back to pure-WSGI
mode for parity with the rest of the services. This adjusts our jobs to fit
with that so that we're testing the default, but also the standalone case.
After this change, we end up with the following for the vanilla devstack
jobs:

 - The "-import" job, which takes the devstack default of WSGI mode,
   with all the tweaks required for import to be enabled. It configures
   import conversion to raw, metadata injection, and confirms that with a
   post-run check for that metadata.
 - The "-import-standalone" job, which inherits all the behaviors from
   the job above, but configures glance in standalone mode.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/742884
Change-Id: Ia3fb8aba83bbd7a1399aef136ce8857b14d08435

subject: Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

[{'created': '2020-09-29 10:29:26.000000000', 'message': "Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because
testtools required unittest2, which still included it. With testtools
removing Python 2.7 support [3][4], we will lose support for
assertItemsEqual, so we should switch to use assertCountEqual.

[1] - https://bugs.python.org/issue17866
[2] - https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/d9921cb6e3cd
[3] - testing-cabal/testtools#286

commit_message:
Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because
testtools required unittest2, which still included it. With testtools
removing Python 2.7 support [3][4], we will lose support for
assertItemsEqual, so we should switch to use assertCountEqual.

[1] - https://bugs.python.org/issue17866
[2] - https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/d9921cb6e3cd
[3] - testing-cabal/testtools#286
[4] - testing-cabal/testtools#277

Change-Id: I133e5b7f26167451c8ccce9492ba750a440bc837

Based on last qos meeting discussion let's go back to the approach where placement call (allocation update) happens after db transaction (AFTER_UPDATE event).

Pros&cons of this approach (with BEFORE_UPDATE event):
pros:
 * placement REST call is befor db transaction
 * if placement update fails port update fails, no db rollback is needed.

cons:
 * if port update fails in later phase (like db error, etc..) no way to rollback the changes in placement."}, {'account_id': 8313, 'date': '2020-09-03 12:59:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 29963, 'date': '2020-09-03 13:41:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ieb0a95af10dd8e054254618a9021e69aca68191a

commit_message:
Configure rsyncd without pid file for Swift

There are known issues with stale pid file handling in rsyncd [1],
which by consequence cause Swift to not start.

This change disables use of pid file completely when deployed by
the swift-storage conainer and depends on the addition of such
a feature in the puppetlabs-rsync module [2]

1. https://www.mail-archive.com/rsync@lists.samba.org/msg32735.html
2. https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppetlabs-rsync/pull/120

Closes-Bug: 1896605
Change-Id: I81ad92793b8f115c046a678f4b2cc51d1014e3b6
(cherry picked from commit 43b5b0875d07bd3db29e83661aa32742dbef3544)

[{'created': '2020-09-14 16:03:02.000000000', 'message': 'PowerMax Driver - Legacy volumes fail to live migrate

The fix moves the legacy shared volume from the masking view
structure in Ocata and sooner (when SMI-S was supported) to staging
masking view(s) in Pike and later releases (U4P REST).
In Ocata, the live migration process shared the storage group,
containing the volume, among the different compute Nodes. In PIke,
we changed the masking view structure to facilitate a cleaner live
migration process where only the volume is migrated and not all the
other volumes in the storage group. The staging storage group and
masking views facilitate a seamless live migration operation in
upgraded releases.

Change-Id: I4d28d8ed2375f68eed511de5c25898362eac1def
Closes-Bug: #1867163
(cherry picked from commit 197e024747ca04daeb35a9eaa9f1350089211ea3)

commit_message:
PowerMax Driver - Legacy volumes fail to live migrate

The fix moves the legacy shared volume from the masking view
structure in Ocata and sooner (when SMI-S was supported) to staging
masking view(s) in Pike and later releases (U4P REST).
In Ocata, the live migration process shared the storage group,
containing the volume, among the different compute Nodes. In PIke,
we changed the masking view structure to facilitate a cleaner live
migration process where only the volume is migrated and not all the
other volumes in the storage group. The staging storage group and
masking views facilitate a seamless live migration operation in
upgraded releases.

Change-Id: I4d28d8ed2375f68eed511de5c25898362eac1def
Closes-Bug: #1867163
(cherry picked from commit 197e024747ca04daeb35a9eaa9f1350089211ea3)

[{'created': '2020-08-20 01:30:52.000000000', 'message': "Fix flavor NotFound in test_resize_server_revert_deleted_flavor

commit_message:
Fix flavor NotFound in test_resize_server_revert_deleted_flavor

Running test_resize_server_revert_deleted_flavor with microversion > 2.46
fails with flavor NotFound error, because after microversion 2.46, 'id'
is not in server's flavor info, so we can only compare flavor details,
but if flavor is deleted, getting flavor info will throw NotFound error.
So we should save the original flavor details before flavor is deleted
for the later comparison.

Change-Id: I88cc46711d6331e7a65b17bf55e1205b333a63d0
Closes-Bug: #1892166

commit_message:
Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because
testtools required unittest2, which still included it. With testtools
removing Python 2.7 support [3][4], we will lose support for
assertItemsEqual, so we should switch to use assertCountEqual.

[1] - https://bugs.python.org/issue17866
[2] - https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/d9921cb6e3cd
[3] - testing-cabal/testtools#286
[4] - testing-cabal/testtools#277

Change-Id: I93cf4263c09959c30994bbb06614ab54eb98120e

commit_message:
Fix import line location

There were two issues with the previous implementation of
_add_import_for_test_uuid():

1) Sometimes the import line was added to the end of the file.
   For example,
     - when the import line belonged to the first line,
     - when there was no tempest import line.

2) Sometimes the import line was not added to the correct import
   group (2nd - related third party imports) defined by the pep8
   style guide.

This patch makes sure that both issues 1) and 2) are solved. The
import line is now by default added between the tempest imports.
If there is no tempest import the import line is added to the
second import group.

Change-Id: Icbac702d295f7f75b3259ad68dd2345cc1e4d90b

commit_message:
[NetApp] Fix HTTPS connection for python 3.7

With python3.7, the eventlet is breaking the ssl.py, so the https
is not working. This patch fixes it by changing the request library
(urllib by requests), the new library can be built over the
pyopenssl.py instead of ssl.py.

Closes-Bug: #1878993
Change-Id: I9c0b1f332ead25634f3dc3aebfdc8b51dfbc4178
(cherry picked from commit 29622725e411402b835e3e45328a9e695f75ea78)
(cherry picked from commit 2dbdace6616d34bfb43c72905dda04c91bcf1dc6)

"}, {'created': '2020-05-30 13:43:25.000000000', 'message': "Disable log in wait task for async task execution

Currently we don't disable log in wait task for async task execution,
but this causes that all outputs of async tasks shown as the output
of wait tasks when async tasks are finished.
This causes huge length of line in output because all of the output of
paunch command are packed into one line by ansible, and this makes it

Also, there alreadly exists a subsequent task to show stdout/stderr
output of async tasks in original format, thus these outputs in wait
tasks are not useful but just annoying.

but this causes that all outputs of async tasks shown as the output
of wait tasks when async tasks are finished. What is worse, these
outputs are packed in one line by ansible and appears as hugely long
lines.
However, there alreadly exists a subsequent task to show stdout/stderr

tasks are not useful but just annoying.

commit_message:
Disable log in wait task for async task execution

Currently we don't disable log in wait task for async task execution,
but this causes that all outputs of async tasks shown as the output
of wait tasks when async tasks are finished. What is worse, these
outputs are packed in one line by ansible and appears as hugely long
lines.
However, there alreadly exists a subsequent task to show stdout/stderr
output of async tasks in original format, thus these outputs in wait
tasks are not useful but just annoying.

Change-Id: Ie81ca5056777d2e3e56602000fc5d681b2abab85

commit_message:
Fix pdns4 devstack plugin

We no longer need to deal with xenial or older distro versions, so we
can assume that we can always install pdns4 from the distro directly
and don't need the distro version check any longer.

Drop a config option that was removed in pdns 4.2.x.

Use mysql credentials correctly.

Change-Id: I90af3a092296f943509833608f25522b6f8e9ab6

commit_message:
Use unittest.mock instead of mock

The mock third party library was needed for mock support in py2
runtimes. Since we now only support py36 and later, we can use the
standard lib unittest.mock module instead.

Change-Id: I6bdf38b8b7e63ff8183f0aaccb566d2baa37df56

commit_message:
fix database sync always get the wrong  value

we create a default pool  when exec database sync, and get the
default_pool_id from designate.conf, but we did not register this
opt before using  it, so we always get the default value which is
wrong

Change-Id: I500c932a502db24332aad95c54713b7056bc1df4
Closes-Bug: 1881277
Related-Bug: https://bugs.launchpad.net/kolla-ansible/+bug/1855877

documentation using make.

commit_message:
Create tox environment to build pdf documentation

This patch enables building .pdf documentation using new 'pdf-docs'
tox environment. The newly created tox environment creates latex
source codes using sphinx-build and then builds the pdf
documentation using make.

Also, this patch makes minor changes in the documentation source
code to make sure that the .pdf and .html documentation looks
good.

Story: 2006070
Task: 35454

Change-Id: I74a151163812a3dc8fde9f85739882a54ad11fd3

Clean debug-py35 up from tox.ini

commit_message:
Use unittest.mock instead of mock

The mock third party library was needed for mock support in py2
runtimes. Since we now only support py36 and later, we can use the
standard lib unittest.mock module instead.

Change-Id: If1d3827f558118b6070a96358909980f7278dd42

commit_message:
Make database backups work with openstack Train

This PS fixes a problem with the main backup script in the helm-toolkit,
which tries to create a swift container using the SWIFT_URL. The problem
is that the SWIFT_URL is malformed because the call to openstack get
catalog list has a different format in Train than it did in Stein. So a
solution that works for both Train and Stein is needed. This patch will
use openstack catalog show instead and will extract the public URL from
that output.

Change-Id: Ic326b0b4717951525e6b17ab015577f28e1d321a

          # Shared services

commit_message:
Simplify default config test

When run in parallel, there is a race condition in which the cleanup of
the generated sample config file may happen while another unit test is
trying to read from it, causing the test to fail[1]. Since both
test_config_default and test_profiler_config_default are simply
asserting properties of the default config file and not testing
different corner cases, it's simplest to combine the two tests and not
worry about when and how the sample file is cleaned up.

[1] https://zuul.opendev.org/t/openstack/build/d870ff2db4b74c21a66b756f4377a0c4/artifacts

Change-Id: If5de3b3499ea73c601e8793cba4fef3441d72f5d

commit_message:
Don't use ansible 2.10.0 for molecule

don't use Ansible 2.10.0 in molecule jobs.

commit_message:
Implement a Minimal role

Add a new role, called "Minimal", which has the strict minimum services
that need to run on a host.
This can be used as a reference when creating custom roles with custom
services (e.g. third party).

Change-Id: I6484d97d0f044de153404516bce0ea7fc2a5f0e1

commit_message:
Create container-puppet-tasks files per step in check mode

In check mode, we still create the container-puppet-tasks json files,
they are later processed, even in dry run.

Change-Id: If999952c6cc0c9bf03ca745bddcf79c395a44e98

commit_message:
Change glance default back to WSGI mode

The situation around glance under WSGI has changed a lot in a week.
We can now run tasks and imports under WSGI, so let's switch the
default back so that glance is consistent (by default) with the
other projects.

Change-Id: I3ae285b2ac4972c0b8abaccfc7c0ede0e1c49bf1

revisions:
[{'created': '2018-07-20 13:01:08.000000000', 'message': 'WIP Arm64

* Partially re-tools networking to be compatible with qemu-system-aarch64
* Implements a download of a grubaa64 binary to aid in facilitating booting
* Removes un-needed second serial port from test VM
* Updates testvm profile in a configuration that *hopefully* can be swapped
  between x86_64 and aarch64. This will allow for an easier transition and
  adaptation to x86_64 UEFI support as time goes on.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/578959
Change-Id: I1e81ac55cac9005f3e678fb412be583431986982
'}, {'created': '2018-07-21 16:01:01.000000000', 'message': 'Initial Arm64 support

In order to support... quite a bit of work is needed.

* Partially re-tools networking to be compatible with qemu-system-aarch64,
  which is based on some of the functionality from the neutron support
  patch series.
* Removes un-needed second serial port from test VM
* Updates testvm profile in a configuration that *hopefully* can be swapped
  between x86_64 and aarch64. This will allow for an easier transition and
  adaptation to x86_64 UEFI support as time goes on.
* Builds x86_64 and aarch64 EFI binaries. The x86_64 can be implemented later.
* Includes notes for future revisions/changes
* Boots ipxe on the aarch64 VM! \o/
  This is as far as we can go without starting on an arm machine or having
  arm images... :(
* Changes the VM to use PCIe, which is present on ARM vms, but not the VMs
  we were using for testing.
* Contains commented out blocks for grubaa64.efi download. This would be helpful
  with grub based EFI boot testing, however we cannot test introspection without
  fallback. Alternatively we could, in the future... chain to ipxe from grub.
  This basis may be useful for x86_64 EFI later on.

This currently cannot be used to build a cross-os image. i.e. To test aarch64,
you either need images that you can download or build locally.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/578959
Change-Id: I1e81ac55cac9005f3e678fb412be583431986982

  we were using for testing.
* Contains commented out blocks for grubaa64.efi download. This would be
  helpful with grub based EFI boot testing, however we cannot test
  introspection without fallback. Alternatively we could, in the future...
  chain to ipxe from grub. This basis may be useful for x86_64 EFI later on.

This currently cannot be used to build a cross-os image. i.e. To test aarch64,
you either need images that you can download or build locally.

commit_message:
Initial Arm64 support

In order to support... quite a bit of work is needed.

* Partially re-tools networking to be compatible with qemu-system-aarch64,
  which is based on some of the functionality from the neutron support
  patch series.
* Removes un-needed second serial port from test VM
* Delineats x86_64 and aarch64 template files as the machine types
  for x86_64 seem to lack PCIe support, and the VM creation fails as such.
* Builds x86_64 and aarch64 EFI binaries. The x86_64 can be
  implemented later.
* Includes notes for future revisions/changes
* Boots ipxe on the aarch64 VM! \o/
  This is as far as we can go without starting on an arm machine or having
  arm images... :(
* Changes the VM to use PCIe, which is present on ARM vms, but not the VMs
  we were using for testing.
* Contains commented out blocks for grubaa64.efi download. This would be
  helpful with grub based EFI boot testing, however we cannot test
  introspection without fallback. Alternatively we could, in the future...
  chain to ipxe from grub. This basis may be useful for x86_64 EFI later on.

This currently cannot be used to build a cross-os image. i.e. To test aarch64,
you either need images that you can download or build locally.

Depends-On: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/578959
Change-Id: I1e81ac55cac9005f3e678fb412be583431986982

commit_message:
CI: Tune down multinode concurrency

Looks like we may be tryign to run through multinode
with too high of a concurrency becuase we have had
a few failures where job scheduling failed.

As such, turning it down to two jobs which should
give the job enough time to wrap up between phases.

Change-Id: I961890dd788dce67f54ab0ac1c0a74fee4a763f8

commit_message:
Add collectd-libpod-stats to image

This patch adds the installation of collectd-libpod-stats as part of the
collectd image. The package is available in the centos-opstools repo.

Collectd-libpod-stats monitors resource usage of running containers on a
host, specifically those managed by the libpod library.

Upstream: https://github.com/pleimer/collectd-libpod-stats

Change-Id: I22501d522c9353a61830b3b7063f2a91c1a7fc50
Signed-off-by: pleimer <pfbleimer@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Drop tasks meant to run run_os_net_config.sh

The script has been dropped now. So we should drop these
permanently skipped tasks. Also adds check to not run the
async task in check mode.

Fixes the molecule tests and modifies bindep.txt to
install python3 packages on fedora to test locally.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/751720/
Change-Id: I8a535b2df9716d083b2c28438d1006891c05da1c

Currently if do_next_deploy/clean_step fails, the failure is swallowed
by eventlet since they're run in a new thread. This 1) is incorrect,
2) leads to nodes stuck in DEPLOYING/CLEANING.

"}]
commit_message:
Do not silently ignore exceptions when running next steps

Currently if do_next_deploy/clean_step fails, the failure is swallowed
by eventlet since they're run in a new thread. This 1) is incorrect,
2) leads to nodes stuck in DEPLOYING/CLEANING.

Also update logging in agent_base to be able to easier spot similar
problems.

Change-Id: I0282c9e06c54a173efc666cd8df25cf573afb394

Build succeeded.

- neutron http://cloudbase-ci.com/neutron/753833/1 : SUCCESS in 2h 09m 50s'}, {'account_id': 11952, 'date': '2020-09-24 12:22:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Patch Set 1 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 23567, 'date': '2020-09-24 12:42:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

tested it locally and seems to fix the issue'}, {'account_id': 23567, 'date': '2020-09-24 12:53:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 23804, 'date': '2020-09-24 14:08:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Initially I'm against this patch because we can consider that Neutron owns the OVN deployment so nobody is expected to write anything there :)

I believe that behind this, there is a more fundamental problem that is that the OVN plugin maintenance task is attempting to fix a resource that has not been created by it. Instead, it was created by the Octavia OVN provider.

What I'd suggest is to modify the maintenace task in the OVN Neutron plugin to only attempt to fix resources that have been created by it. ie, add some mechanism or attend to device_id or something else that allows this differentiation.

This will not only fix the issue at hand but will set the grounds for the OVN Octavia provider to have its own maintenance task.

What do you think?"}, {'account_id': 6773, 'date': '2020-09-24 14:15:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

were not created/modified by the update.'}, {'account_id': 11952, 'date': '2020-09-24 16:48:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

> Initially I'm against this patch because we can consider that
 > Neutron owns the OVN deployment so nobody is expected to write
 > anything there :)
 > 
 > I believe that behind this, there is a more fundamental problem
 > that is that the OVN plugin maintenance task is attempting to fix a
 > resource that has not been created by it. Instead, it was created
 > by the Octavia OVN provider.
 > 
 > What I'd suggest is to modify the maintenace task in the OVN
 > Neutron plugin to only attempt to fix resources that have been
 > created by it. ie, add some mechanism or attend to device_id or
 > something else that allows this differentiation.
 > 
 > This will not only fix the issue at hand but will set the grounds
 > for the OVN Octavia provider to have its own maintenance task.
 > 
 > What do you think?

I would like to separate the bugfix from a much bigger work, if at all possible.

With that in mind, I think this patchset offers a generic solution w/out complicating the maintenance task. The ovn-octavia-provider expects the external_ids to be useable by it. Otherwise it will need to find another place to store its data. 

It would be good to hear from more folks on this, but I cannot understand why external_ids cannot be shared among all friends of the neutron clan. Think of how sad OVN would feel if it could not use external_ids from the open_vswitch table. :^)"}, {'account_id': 11952, 'date': '2020-09-24 18:35:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Adding one clarification on this discussion. The code that sets [1] and clears [2] the value being lost in the port_update is
part of the neutron codebase. ovn-octavia-provider is passively paying attention to it and deciding [3] how to configure the
load balancer from that. So I would argue that networking-ovn / neutron is the one that is shooting itself in the foot by prematurely
removing that key pair value from the LSP's external ids. Hope that may convince folks that this Gerrit is okay.

So yes, this patch is good! Thanks!


On the other hand, I still believe that as a follow up, we need to make the maintenance task to pay attention only to the resources on its domain. commit_message:
[OVN] update_port should not remove values from external_ids

Prior to this patch, the OVNClient implementation for neutron's
update_port was setting the external_ids of the affected logical
switch port to a hard-coded dictionary. This meant that any key
value pairs that were not listed there would simply get removed.
This would make it impossible for any other users of the
external_id to have a reliable way of storing its data. One of
such users could be the ovn-octavia-provider.

Closes-Bug: #1896827
Change-Id: Ie580534e4d91f1ca2e1dc8331632d49d4720e7ba

subject: Reduce the use of SQLAlchemy connection pooling
messages: [{'account_id': 14826, 'date': '2020-09-29 08:23:56.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 14826, 'date': '2020-09-29 10:30:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 30491, 'date': '2020-09-29 15:25:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-29 08:23:56.000000000', 'message': "Reduce the use of SQLAlchemy connection pooling

When the internal VIP is moved in the event of a failure of the active
controller, OpenStack services can become unresponsive as they try to
talk with MariaDB using connections from the SQLAlchemy pool.

It has been argued that OpenStack doesn't really need to use connection
pooling with MariaDB [1]. This commit reduces the use of connection
pooling via two configuration options:

- max_pool_size is set to 1 to allow only a single connection in the
  pool (it is not possible to disable connection pooling entirely via
  oslo.db, and max_pool_size = 0 means unlimited pool size)
- lower connection_recycle_time from the default of one hour to 10
  seconds, which means the single connection in the pool will be
  recreated regularly

These settings have shown better reactivity of the system in the event
of a failover.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/061808.html

commit_message:
Reduce the use of SQLAlchemy connection pooling

When the internal VIP is moved in the event of a failure of the active
controller, OpenStack services can become unresponsive as they try to
talk with MariaDB using connections from the SQLAlchemy pool.

It has been argued that OpenStack doesn't really need to use connection
pooling with MariaDB [1]. This commit reduces the use of connection
pooling via two configuration options:

- max_pool_size is set to 1 to allow only a single connection in the
  pool (it is not possible to disable connection pooling entirely via
  oslo.db, and max_pool_size = 0 means unlimited pool size)
- lower connection_recycle_time from the default of one hour to 10
  seconds, which means the single connection in the pool will be
  recreated regularly

These settings have shown better reactivity of the system in the event
of a failover.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/061808.html

Change-Id: Ib6a62d4428db9b95569314084090472870417f3d
Closes-Bug: #1896635
(cherry picked from commit c81772024c70b84564cfddb29645390ae378498f)

commit_message:
allow to specify drivername for postgres db

in newer versions of sqlalchemy a drivername is required to
avoid a warning. For postgres the driver is psycopg2.
The driver is optional.

2) This approach will break with the deploy steps split, so maybe we should add retries to AgentClient._command?"}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2020-06-25 17:59:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> 1) We shouldn't be able to reach continue_deploy when an operation
 > is running, there must be a bug somewhere else. Essentially,
 > continue_deploy is the first thing we do right now, what is even
 > running there?
 > 

I'm not sure why you think we can't. Heartbeats occur independently in separate thread on the agent.

The guard to prevent hitting continue deploy is actually check agent command status.

We're in DEPLOYWAIT as we've already called continue_deploy for the very first time.

Heartbeats continue to run as that first command executes.

Heartbeat comes in and ends up at:

https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/drivers/modules/agent_base.py#L505 which calls deploy_has_started

https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/drivers/modules/agent.py#L174 is deploy_has_started, which calls the agent to determine the current command status.

https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/drivers/modules/agent.py#L175 is the call to the IPA api for get_commands_status

IPA returns nothing because it literally has no output yet.

We then end up calling continue_deploy again

https://github.com/openstack/ironic/blob/master/ironic/drivers/modules/agent.py#L199

Which ultimately means we end up hitting prepare_image on IPA, which then tanks the entire deployment as the first command is still executing in IPA.


 > 2) This approach will break with the deploy steps split, so maybe
 > we should add retries to AgentClient._command?

We already have _command retries and that wouldn't help this problem at all. The problem is the very first command is still running, thus IPA has no command status output to report. Truly the bug is the entire reliance on IPA command output to determine if we've actually started. :\

If you could elaborate on how you see this breaking the deploy steps split, that would be extremely helpful because I'm not sure I understand what your trying to convey."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2020-06-25 21:30:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> IPA returns nothing because it literally has no output yet.

I need to look into this statement tomorrow morning, I was under impression it wasn't true. If that's the case, many things are actually racy in ironic.

A good thing is: with deploy steps we get rid of these shady functions."}, {'account_id': 10239, 'date': '2020-06-26 07:41:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> IPA returns nothing because it literally has no output yet.

This does not seem to be correct, we're recording the command information before returning from execute_command: https://opendev.org/openstack/ironic-python-agent/src/branch/master/ironic_python_agent/extensions/base.py#L276. By the time the node gets to DEPLOYWAIT, the information about the 'prepare_image' command must already be there."}, {'account_id': 11655, 'date': '2020-06-26 19:09:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Handle "agent is busy" errors during deployment

Deployment heartbeat operations continue while the agent
performs the requested work. When there are intermittent
or transient connectivity issues, the agent may still be
trying to complete the very first command which it was
requested which means it has no current status to report.

When new commands are issued in this state, the conductor
has no way of knowing that this was already in-progress,
so we need to recognize when this is happening and not fail
the deployment operation.

rhbz#1850213

Change-Id: I537dfa36e730f6d5a0688a279d4df16ea053676b

commit_message:
Use the utility host for db setup tasks

Move it to the service setup host (defaults to utility[0]) instead
of the galera[0] host, and use galera_address (defaults to internal VIP)
as the endpoint instead of a local connection on the db host.

Change-Id: I1171b6a45563e4eccf45e8840e5dd332001ff3b7

Remove CI jobs to allow db setup patch to merge

This requires patches to merge at the same time in os_panko,
os_gnocchi and os_aodh which is not possible.

commit_message:
Minimize ceph-daemon image size

These changes are to minimize the ceph-daemon image size as is
recommended by industry standard best practices. The main changes
are the removal of various debugging tools such as:

valgrind
hexedit
sysstat
dstat
iperf

as well as compilers and debuggers

gcc
gcc-7
cpp-7
gdb

Etcdctl and forego are also removed.

Change-Id: I9502c5f297b1bfcdaafb82ae438f3ba6382c2c64

subject: Prefer unversioned endpoint for cinder v3 API
reviewers: [{'_account_id': 6796, 'name': 'Giulio Fidente', 'email': 'gfidente@redhat.com', 'username': 'gfidente'}, {'_account_id': 6816, 'name': 'Jesse Pretorius', 'email': 'jesse@odyssey4.me', 'username': 'jesse-pretorius'}, {'_account_id': 21129, 'name': 'Alan Bishop', 'email': 'abishop@redhat.com', 'username': 'ASBishop'}, {'_account_id': 22348, 'name': 'Zuul', 'username': 'zuul', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}, {'_account_id': 23181, 'name': 'RDO Third Party CI', 'email': 'dmsimard+rdothirdparty@redhat.com', 'username': 'rdothirdparty', 'tags': ['SERVICE_USER']}]
messages:
[{'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2020-07-06 10:08:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 21129, 'date': '2020-07-06 14:18:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

But cinder has always used versioned endpoints (I'm not sure why). The non-versioned one was associated with the v1 API, which is no longer supported.

There's a long backstory here:

Cinder's v1 API was completely removed in queens, but the puppet-cinder code wasn't updated until stein [1]. For rocky and queens, [2] and [3] were added to THT in an attempt to suppress puppet-cinder from creating the v1 entries

[1] https://review.opendev.org/636456
[2] https://review.opendev.org/640480
[3] https://review.opendev.org/644550

Unfortunately, the version of tempest used for queens falsely assumed a "volume" service would always be present. This required another THT change in queens to create a "volume" service that used the v3's endpoint.

[4] https://review.opendev.org/649084

Post queens, tripleo should be creating the v2 and v3 service names and endpoints. When upgrading from queens, the unversioned "volume" service will still be present, and could (should?) be manually removed. We did not want tripleo to automatically remove entries from the catalog.

Sorry for the long ramble, but I don't understand the problem this patch is trying to solve.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2020-07-06 14:45:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> But cinder has always used versioned endpoints (I'm not sure why).
 > The non-versioned one was associated with the v1 API, which is no
 > longer supported.
 > 
 > There's a long backstory here:
 > 
 > Cinder's v1 API was completely removed in queens, but the
 > puppet-cinder code wasn't updated until stein [1]. For rocky and
 > queens, [2] and [3] were added to THT in an attempt to suppress
 > puppet-cinder from creating the v1 entries
 > 
 > [1] https://review.opendev.org/636456
 > [2] https://review.opendev.org/640480
 > [3] https://review.opendev.org/644550
 > 
 > Unfortunately, the version of tempest used for queens falsely
 > assumed a "volume" service would always be present. This required
 > another THT change in queens to create a "volume" service that used
 > the v3's endpoint.
 > 
 > [4] https://review.opendev.org/649084
 > 
 > Post queens, tripleo should be creating the v2 and v3 service names
 > and endpoints. When upgrading from queens, the unversioned "volume"
 > service will still be present, and could (should?) be manually
 > removed. We did not want tripleo to automatically remove entries
 > from the catalog.
 > 
 > Sorry for the long ramble, but I don't understand the problem this
 > patch is trying to solve.

after the upgrade we end up with "volume", "volumev2" and "volumev3", which is causing issues like https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1853281

I was about to ask why we don't remove the "volume" endpoints but I read you saying we didn't want tripleo to do it, why so?'}, {'account_id': 21129, 'date': '2020-07-06 15:08:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

> > Sorry for the long ramble, but I don't understand the problem
 > this
 > > patch is trying to solve.
 > 
 > after the upgrade we end up with "volume", "volumev2" and
 > "volumev3", which is causing issues like https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1853281

I think you'll find all those catalog entries were present before the upgrade. I suspect the upgrade code that trips over this didn't anticipate the situation would occur. On a clean train deployment you should only see the "volume2" and "volume3" services.

 > 
 > I was about to ask why we don't remove the "volume" endpoints but I
 > read you saying we didn't want tripleo to do it, why so?

The decision to not remove the v1 (volume) endpoint was discussed in the puppet-cinder patch [5].

[5] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/636456/2/manifests/keystone/auth.pp@227

But that was a long time ago, and maybe removing the service and endpoint is something that tripleo *should* do. It's probably OK for tripleo to be more opinionated than puppet-cinder.

I recommend investigating tripleo removing the obsolete "volume" service, or enhancing the upgrade code mentioned in the rhbz so that it handles it.'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2020-07-06 16:01:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

> I recommend investigating tripleo removing the obsolete "volume"
 > service, or enhancing the upgrade code mentioned in the rhbz so
 > that it handles it.

ack let's try that then'}, {'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2020-09-29 16:13:27.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

not the right fix; rather have the external scripts deal with the possibility of multiple services for volume*'}]

[{'created': '2020-07-06 10:08:53.000000000', 'message': 'Prefer unversioned endpoint for cinder v3 API

Using "volumev3" service type is not best practice and causes issues
when upgrading from queens, where we set the v3 service type to
be just "volume"

Change-Id: I04767e83a1430dfc4dfdd5eb302030e6c673c8b6
Closes-Bug: 1886407
'}]
commit_message:
Prefer unversioned endpoint for cinder v3 API

Using "volumev3" service type is not best practice and causes issues
when upgrading from queens, where we set the v3 service type to
be just "volume"

Change-Id: I04767e83a1430dfc4dfdd5eb302030e6c673c8b6
Closes-Bug: 1886407

Unpin flake8

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-08-18 17:24:50.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet should be monkey patched as early as possible

Eventlet documentation indicates that monkey patching should be
done as early in an application's lifecycle as possible. Currently,
instead of proactively monkey_patching, IPA is relying on libraries
to monkey_patch when needed.

This can cause issues when libraries are imported by IPA before
having an opportunity to be monkey patched. By doing this as early
as possible in the application lifecycle, we are using eventlet as
documentation suggests and minimize inconsistent behavior.

Change-Id: Ibcde99de64bb7e95d5df63a42a4ca4999f0c4c9b
"}, {'created': '2020-08-19 20:25:22.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet should be monkey patched as early as possible

Eventlet documentation indicates that monkey patching should be
done as early in an application's lifecycle as possible. Currently,
instead of proactively monkey_patching, IPA is relying on libraries
to monkey_patch when needed.

This can cause issues when libraries are imported by IPA before
having an opportunity to be monkey patched. By doing this as early
as possible in the application lifecycle, we are using eventlet as
documentation suggests and minimize inconsistent behavior.

Also, according to ironic commit
556b1d0871d01ab17715955bef566c99bcf6bedc we should not be calling
to eventlet, except for in init for the CLI.

Change-Id: Ibcde99de64bb7e95d5df63a42a4ca4999f0c4c9b
"}, {'created': '2020-08-20 20:24:45.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet should be monkey patched as early as possible

Eventlet documentation indicates that monkey patching should be
done as early in an application's lifecycle as possible. Currently,
instead of proactively monkey_patching, IPA is relying on libraries
to monkey_patch when needed.

This can cause issues when libraries are imported by IPA before
having an opportunity to be monkey patched. By doing this as early
as possible in the application lifecycle, we are using eventlet as
documentation suggests and minimize inconsistent behavior.

Eventlet patches out select.poll(), so this also changes heartbeats
to use select.select via the selectors module instead.

Also, according to ironic commit
556b1d0871d01ab17715955bef566c99bcf6bedc we should not be calling
to eventlet, except for in init for the CLI.

Change-Id: Ibcde99de64bb7e95d5df63a42a4ca4999f0c4c9b
"}, {'created': '2020-08-20 20:50:35.000000000', 'message': "Eventlet should be monkey patched as early as possible

Eventlet documentation indicates that monkey patching should be
done as early in an application's lifecycle as possible. Currently,
instead of proactively monkey_patching, IPA is relying on libraries
to monkey_patch when needed.

This can cause issues when libraries are imported by IPA before
having an opportunity to be monkey patched. By doing this as early
as possible in the application lifecycle, we are using eventlet as
documentation suggests and minimize inconsistent behavior.

Eventlet patches out select.poll(), so this also changes heartbeats
to use select.select via the selectors module instead.

Also, according to ironic commit
556b1d0871d01ab17715955bef566c99bcf6bedc we should not be calling
to eventlet, except for in init for the CLI. It's now been moved
into the cmd and test init files.

This can cause issues when libraries are imported by IPA before
having an opportunity to be monkey patched. By doing this as early
as possible in the application lifecycle, we are using eventlet as
documentation suggests and minimize inconsistent behavior.

Eventlet patches out select.poll(), so this also changes heartbeats
to use select.select via the selectors module instead.

Change-Id: Ibcde99de64bb7e95d5df63a42a4ca4999f0c4c9b

having an opportunity to be monkey patched. By doing this as early

documentation suggests and minimize inconsistent behavior.

to use clock time to perform heartbeats. This was the original

commit_message:
Simplify heartbeating by removing use of select()

Heartbeating in IPA has used select.poll() for years to workaround
a bug where changing the time in the ramdisk could cause heartbeats
to stop and never resume.

Now that IPA syncs time at start and exit, this workaround is no
longer needed. So instead, we'll revert to using threading.Event()
in order to make the code simpler and easier to understand.

Since we need this to be an eventlet-event, and not a standard-thread
event, also monkey_patch threading.

Additionally, there were a few completely unused backoff interval
values set, that were never applied. In respect of maintaining the
5+ years old behavior of not doing error backoffs, that code was
removed instead of being made to work.

Change-Id: Ibcde99de64bb7e95d5df63a42a4ca4999f0c4c9b

commit_message:
tripleo_profile_tasks: add a final line break

If a trace occurs, a final line break is visually useful to know when
the task profiling ends. The trace will be show *after* the callback so
we reduce confusion where the problem is.

Change-Id: Ibe21bdf046f71ce45f0fd36068635c4d954da5f2
(cherry picked from commit db3ff367f51cdd2e1251f2e87a72fc0db852ecf1)

[{'created': '2020-09-29 08:21:20.000000000', 'message': "Reduce the use of SQLAlchemy connection pooling

When the internal VIP is moved in the event of a failure of the active
controller, OpenStack services can become unresponsive as they try to
talk with MariaDB using connections from the SQLAlchemy pool.

It has been argued that OpenStack doesn't really need to use connection
pooling with MariaDB [1]. This commit reduces the use of connection
pooling via two configuration options:

- max_pool_size is set to 1 to allow only a single connection in the
  pool (it is not possible to disable connection pooling entirely via
  oslo.db, and max_pool_size = 0 means unlimited pool size)
- lower connection_recycle_time from the default of one hour to 10
  seconds, which means the single connection in the pool will be
  recreated regularly

These settings have shown better reactivity of the system in the event
of a failover.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/061808.html

Change-Id: Ib6a62d4428db9b95569314084090472870417f3d
Closes-Bug: #1896635
(cherry picked from commit c81772024c70b84564cfddb29645390ae378498f)
"}]
commit_message:
Reduce the use of SQLAlchemy connection pooling

When the internal VIP is moved in the event of a failure of the active
controller, OpenStack services can become unresponsive as they try to
talk with MariaDB using connections from the SQLAlchemy pool.

It has been argued that OpenStack doesn't really need to use connection
pooling with MariaDB [1]. This commit reduces the use of connection
pooling via two configuration options:

- max_pool_size is set to 1 to allow only a single connection in the
  pool (it is not possible to disable connection pooling entirely via
  oslo.db, and max_pool_size = 0 means unlimited pool size)
- lower connection_recycle_time from the default of one hour to 10
  seconds, which means the single connection in the pool will be
  recreated regularly

These settings have shown better reactivity of the system in the event
of a failover.

[1] http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2015-April/061808.html

Change-Id: Ib6a62d4428db9b95569314084090472870417f3d
Closes-Bug: #1896635
(cherry picked from commit c81772024c70b84564cfddb29645390ae378498f)

commit_message:
Upgrade mon packages immediately

Instead of deferring the upgrading of packages
when doing a release upgrade, do them immediately
and only defer daemon restarts. This is to avoid
any api incompatibilities between newer mons and
older clients.

Change-Id: Idf77871561fa14ad61e0c7901eeb333254e37012
Closes-Bug: #1897594

Fix deprecated 'idrac' interface '__init__'s

This change fixes the deprecated 'idrac' hardware interface
implementation '__init__' methods to call their base class '__init__'
methods before emitting a log message warning about their deprecation.

Story: 2008197
Task: 40977
Change-Id: Ic6e2b6744850d429fae2d353a91649ea68371a59

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because

commit_message:
Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because
testtools required unittest2, which still included it. With testtools
removing Python 2.7 support [3][4], we will lose support for
assertItemsEqual, so we should switch to use assertCountEqual.

Change-Id: I091a1d905b1e67c87270ff65addb97769b4fb028

Trouble accessing generated DSA keys

"openstack secret container get http://<container ref here>"
Above command was failing to get container datails with error
   "Unknown container type "dsa"

Closes-Bug:#1749882

I'm afraid puppet-openstack_spec_helper and puppet-openstack-integration are missing, but am not sure how I can deal with them."}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2020-05-08 13:57:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2020-05-08 13:59:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Workflow'}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2020-05-08 14:16:11.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2020-05-08 14:40:02.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 9816, 'date': '2020-05-08 15:15:51.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 9414, 'date': '2020-05-12 00:37:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2020-05-25 17:27:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

pike and ocata are still in extended maintainance [1] and I think the EOL status is defined by the release team as a global step for all deliverables and not only for few of them.

I mean this topic look like to a whole coordination in openstack and the status of deliverables reflect the status of an openstack cycle.

Thierry and Sean will bring a better response than me on this point.

[1] https://releases.openstack.org/'}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2020-06-03 10:57:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Ocata will be unmaintained at starting from tomorrow [1]. 

Also I made a mistake during my previous review, indeed if a branch is marked as Extended Maintenance, that means individual projects can be in state *Maintained*, *Unmaintained* or *End of Life* on that branch so I think it's ok to continue with these changes.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/releases/commit/d1e5e57137baa6e7ebc5e23e6c738a4d4bd4512a"}, {'account_id': 28522, 'date': '2020-06-03 11:18:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

I reviewed all of these changes and everything looks good, however 2 different patches would have been welcome to isolate topics (ocata/pike), anyway +2 for the current patch.'}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2020-09-28 18:59:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+2

recheck

Sorry I have missed this for so long. The dashboard I use for reviews no longer shows things for ocata and pike, so I missed it.

We can approve this now. There is one additional step to follow up with the infra team after this tagging is complete to actually delete the stable/pike and stable/ocata branches. Please do so after this patch merges.

I will wait a day or two to approve though, just to make sure there isn't any reason to hold off on this since it has been so long since it was submitted."}, {'account_id': 16137, 'date': '2020-09-29 12:28:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

Not sure why PTL-Approved got removed, but yeah let's get rid of this :)"}, {'account_id': 11904, 'date': '2020-09-29 12:40:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow+1'}]

The error appears in the following job stanza:

  job:
      name: devstack-minimal
      parent: devstack-base
      description: |
        Minimal devstack base job, intended for use by jobs that need
        less than the normal minimum set of required-projects.
      nodeset: openstack-single-node-focal
      required-projects:
        - opendev.org/openstack/requirements
      vars:
        devstack_localrc:
          # Multinode specific settings
          SERVICE_HOST: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
          HOST_IP: "{{ hostvars['controller']['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"
          PUBLIC_BRIDGE_MTU: '{{ external_bridge_mtu }}'
        devstack_services:
          # Shared services
          dstat: true
          etcd3: true
          memory_tracker: true
          mysql: true
          rabbit: true

        subnode:
          devstack_services:
            # Shared services
            dstat: true
            memory_tracker: true

            HOST_IP: "{{ hostvars[inventory_hostname]['nodepool']['private_ipv4'] }}"

commit_message:
Remove sync_db parameters

Currently initialization of db is implemented as an independent task
in tripleo-heat-templates and not triggered by puppet.
In puppet, all of sync db jobs are implemented by exec resources but
"exec" is not included in puppet_tags enabled, so these implementations
in puppet are never triggered.

This patch removes sync_db parameters from templates because they are
ineffective and misleading.

Change-Id: Id231c612d8ef0ebc27bf87e0b2acbb76d89c9801

commit_message:
Updated/corrected service_status

This patch updates service_status check, importing what was done in
oooq-extras back in 2019[1].

This will allow to actually ensure only tripleo related services are
checked.

The legacy Docker support is still here in order to allow checking on
older releases.

This patch also adds some fancy molecule testing.
[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/637729/

Change-Id: I0b939f2c01324cbdce452d4fd425cbe8e8d676b8
Authored-By: Cedric Jeanneret <cjeanner@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit d633131d60d6db4dcc9a5a5a1864338384f7add1)

commit_message:
Use correct error handler instead of calling process_event('fail')

Drivers should be using error handler deploying_error_handler() or
cleaning_error_handler() from conductor.utils for handling the failures
of deploy or clean step instead of directly calling process_event('fail').
These handlers perform necessary cleaning before moving the node to failed
state.

Change-Id: I5d9b6831137cdef171a9929f144956f741390953

commit_message:
Updated/corrected service_status

This patch updates service_status check, importing what was done in
oooq-extras back in 2019[1].

This will allow to actually ensure only tripleo related services are
checked.

The legacy Docker support is still here in order to allow checking on
older releases.

This patch also adds some fancy molecule testing.
[1] https://review.opendev.org/#/c/637729/

Change-Id: I0b939f2c01324cbdce452d4fd425cbe8e8d676b8
Authored-By: Cedric Jeanneret <cjeanner@redhat.com>

commit_message:
TripleO Victoria R3 release

This is a tripleo release to coincide with RC1, but this is *not*
an RC in particular we are not cutting the victoria branch yet.
Related puppet-tripleo metadata bump at [1] has merged.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/754347
Change-Id: Ia2b655987b646b6d431892e22942ef1dc5849808

[{'created': '2020-09-28 02:49:27.000000000', 'message': 'Use assertCountEqual instead of assertItemsEqual

The assertItemsEqual method has been removed in Python 3.3 [1] but
it was kept alive by unittest2, imported by testtools. For better
compatibility, change to assertCountEqual.

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue17866

Change-Id: I7cd87e0cb6b8baf44f8b255ced98b20e753e8d4c
'}]
commit_message:
Use assertCountEqual instead of assertItemsEqual

The assertItemsEqual method has been removed in Python 3.3 [1] but
it was kept alive by unittest2, imported by testtools. For better
compatibility, change to assertCountEqual.

[1] https://bugs.python.org/issue17866

Change-Id: I7cd87e0cb6b8baf44f8b255ced98b20e753e8d4c

Sync libraries & common files prior to freeze

* charm-helpers sync for classic charms
* charms.ceph sync for ceph charms
* rebuild for reactive charms
* sync tox.ini files as needed
* sync requirements.txt files to sync to standard

commit_message:
Support TLS encryption of RabbitMQ client-server traffic

This change adds support for encryption of communication between
OpenStack services and RabbitMQ. Server certificates are supported, but
currently client certificates are not.

The kolla-ansible certificates command has been updated to support
generating certificates for RabbitMQ for development and testing.

RabbitMQ TLS is enabled in the all-in-one source CI jobs, or when
The Zuul 'tls_enabled' variable is true.

Change-Id: I4f1d04150fb2b5af085b762890092f87ae6076b5
Implements: blueprint message-queue-ssl-support

In order to build containers using TOCI container build role
on centos 7 based content provider, we need
ansible-role-container-registry to set up docker.

In order to install that, We need to include it as a part of
TQE requires.

subject: Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-29 10:21:19.000000000', 'message': "Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because
testtools required unittest2, which still included it. With testtools
removing Python 2.7 support [3][4], we will lose support for
assertItemsEqual, so we should switch to use assertCountEqual.

[1] - https://bugs.python.org/issue17866
[2] - https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/d9921cb6e3cd
[3] - testing-cabal/testtools#286
[4] - testing-cabal/testtools#277

Change-Id: I013e64c579b064bced06832a95d57426c0b3bc99
"}]
commit_message:
Replace assertItemsEqual with assertCountEqual

assertItemsEqual was removed from Python's unittest.TestCase in
Python 3.3 [1][2]. We have been able to use them since then, because
testtools required unittest2, which still included it. With testtools
removing Python 2.7 support [3][4], we will lose support for
assertItemsEqual, so we should switch to use assertCountEqual.

[1] - https://bugs.python.org/issue17866
[2] - https://hg.python.org/cpython/rev/d9921cb6e3cd
[3] - testing-cabal/testtools#286
[4] - testing-cabal/testtools#277

Change-Id: I013e64c579b064bced06832a95d57426c0b3bc99

commit_message:
Align EC usage with best practice

When using erasure coding three pools are needed. One metadata
pool which is replicated, one default data pool which is replicated
and one erasure coded pool.

Add an additional ec-pool-weight option to allow the erasure coded
pool usage to be modelled within the deployment.

The consumer of the share will need to use xattrs to ensure that
the hierarchy of directories and files are stored in EC pool while
leaving the default replicated data pool for file backtraces.

Depends-On: Ib19e545fc676fa9e986f3fddcfb92cf99e778a3f
Depends-On: I48348ab2b6c8952c5e22008a074a60c1f35be952
Change-Id: I1af386d5e1d031f2f0387c7381af683f948172d9
Closes-Bug: #1895154

commit_message:
[goal] Migrate testing to ubuntu focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Fixing:
- bug#1886298
Bump the lower constraints for required deps which added python3.8 support
in their later version.

- Move multinode jobs to focal nodeset

Story: #2007865
Task: #40227

Closes-Bug: #1886298

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/752294/

commit_message:
WIP: force dashboard_frontend to ceph_dashboard_vip

This is because while we have all internal traffic for the dashboard
configured to use the 'storage' network (or 'ctlplane'), we need
the frontend VIP and only that to be eventually configured on a
custom 'storage_dashboard' network, when that exists.

Change-Id: Id41213263d7010ea9daf4b7f59e8ed82461e93a0

subject: Make dashboard backend in HAProxy assume ceph_mgr IPs
messages:
[{'account_id': 6796, 'date': '2020-09-23 14:15:09.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 25402, 'date': '2020-09-28 13:38:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Overall it looks good to me but I'm a little concerned about the following:
[root@controller-0 puppet]# grep -inRE -A 3 "mgr" hieradata/
hieradata/all_nodes.json:126:    "ceph_mgr_bootstrap_node_ip": "192.168.24.24",
hieradata/all_nodes.json:127:    "ceph_mgr_enabled": true,
hieradata/all_nodes.json:128:    "ceph_mgr_node_ips": [
hieradata/all_nodes.json-129-        "192.168.24.24",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-130-        "192.168.24.45",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-131-        "192.168.24.8"
--
hieradata/all_nodes.json:133:    "ceph_mgr_node_names": [
hieradata/all_nodes.json-134-        "controller-0.ctlplane.redhat.local",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-135-        "controller-1.ctlplane.redhat.local",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-136-        "controller-2.ctlplane.redhat.local"
--
hieradata/all_nodes.json:138:    "ceph_mgr_short_bootstrap_node_name": "controller-0",
hieradata/all_nodes.json:139:    "ceph_mgr_short_node_names": [
hieradata/all_nodes.json-140-        "controller-0",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-141-        "controller-1",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-142-        "controller-2"
--
hieradata/all_nodes.json:414:        "ceph_mgr",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-415-        "ceph_mon",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-416-        "ceph_nfs",
hieradata/all_nodes.json-417-        "ceph_osd",
--
hieradata/service_names.json:9:        "ceph_mgr",
hieradata/service_names.json-10-        "ceph_mon",
hieradata/service_names.json-11-        "ceph_nfs",
hieradata/service_names.json-12-        "ceph_rgw",
--
hieradata/service_configs.json:933:    "tripleo::ceph_mgr::firewall_rules": {
hieradata/service_configs.json:934:        "113 ceph_mgr": {
hieradata/service_configs.json-935-            "dport": [
hieradata/service_configs.json-936-                "6800-7300",
hieradata/service_configs.json-937-                "8444"


We defined "ceph_mgr_node_{names,ips}" according to hieradata, but the resulting relevant haproxy
config is:

```
listen ceph_dashboard
  bind 192.168.24.150:8444 transparent ssl crt /etc/pki/tls/certs/haproxy/overcloud-haproxy-storage.pem
  mode http
  balance source
  http-check expect rstatus 2[0-9][0-9]
  http-request set-header X-Forwarded-Proto https if { ssl_fc }
  http-request set-header X-Forwarded-Proto http if !{ ssl_fc }
  http-request set-header X-Forwarded-Port %[dst_port]
  option httpchk HEAD /
  server controller-0.storage.local 172.17.3.126:8444 ca-file /etc/ipa/ca.crt check fall 5 inter 2000 rise 2 ssl verify required verifyhost controller-0.storage.local
  server controller-1.storage.local 172.17.3.59:8444 ca-file /etc/ipa/ca.crt check fall 5 inter 2000 rise 2 ssl verify required verifyhost controller-1.storage.local
  server controller-2.storage.local 172.17.3.88:8444 ca-file /etc/ipa/ca.crt check fall 5 inter 2000 rise 2 ssl verify required verifyhost controller-2.storage.local

```

which is correct because the processes (ceph dashboard mgr module) are enabled on the storage network, but 
it doesn't match the ceph_mgr_node_{names,ips}, and, at the end of the process, looking at the haproxy stats
I see the following:

```
ceph_dashboard   FRONTEND                               0     0     4096  0     0    0     0     OPEN               1              0
ceph_dashboard   controller-0.storage.local      0     0           0     0    0           DOWN      12146    1              0         * L7STS       0         -1                                                                               0
ceph_dashboard   controller-1.storage.local      0     0           0     0    0           DOWN      12146    1              0         L6RSP         0         -1        Server presented an SSL certificate different from the configured one  0
ceph_dashboard   controller-2.storage.local      0     0           0     0    0           DOWN      12146    1              0         L6RSP         0         -1        Server presented an SSL certificate different from the configured one  0
ceph_dashboard   BACKEND                                0     0     410   0     0    0     0     DOWN      12146    1              0                       0         -1                                                                               0
ceph_grafana     FRONTEND                               0     0     4096  0     0    0     0     OPEN               1              0
ceph_grafana     controller-0.storage.local      0     0           0     0    0           UP        12147    1              0         L7OK          0         -1        OK                                                                     0
ceph_grafana     controller-1.storage.local      0     0           0     0    0           UP        12147    1              0         L7OK          0         -1        OK                                                                     0
ceph_grafana     controller-2.storage.local      0     0           0     0    0           UP        12147    1              0         L7OK          0         -1        OK                                                                     0
ceph_grafana     BACKEND                                0     0     410   0     0    0     0     UP        12147    1              0                       0         -1                                                                               0


```

As you can see grafana is ok with that config, but I'm wondering if this error message we see there
("Server presented an SSL certificate different from the configured one") is related to these
ceph_mgr_node_{names,ips} variables.

Make dashboard backend in HAProxy assume ceph_mgr IPs

The dashboard module is enabled by the Ceph MGRs which are always
only listening on the storage frontend network.

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I883027e47e8030aed848875e2c95d351978a2f6b

commit_message:
Add script to covert nic configs to use OS::Heat::Value

This adds a new script to convert jinja rendered nic config
templates to use OS::Heat::Value.

There is lots of duplication of code as tht is not installed
as a python package and can also be extended later to handle
multiple files if required.

Change-Id: I06ef54f70ffcd4fc1e501bf9c8395bbede1c6dda

commit_message:
Don't crash on fetching network policy.

Sometimes, on pod deletion it happens that kuryr network policy CRD
cannot be found anymore, but we get error from K8s API. Let's wait for
API is functional again.

Change-Id: I24255e59fac46ac10ca815b50d6060c395b4bf34

commit_message:
[goal] Migrate testing to ubuntu focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Fixing:
- bug#1886298
Bump the lower constraints for required deps which added python3.8 support
in their later version.

- Move multinode jobs to focal nodeset

Story: #2007865
Task: #40227

Closes-Bug: #1886298

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal>

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/752294/

Change-Id: Iec953f3294087cd0b628b701ad3d684cea61c057
